#Text=Lipa
#Text=Lipa is a city in Batangas in the Philippines ; it is the largest city in the province .

#Text=The city lies approximately in the center of the province , with Malvar to the north , San Pablo and Alaminos ( in Laguna ) , and San Antonio ( in Quezon ) to the east , Padre Garcia , San Jose and Ibaan to the south , and Cuenca , Mataasnakahoy , and Taal Lake to the west .
#Text=Understand
#Text=The articles covers also the nearby towns , while independent municipalities , are commonly associated with the city .
#Text=Locals generally speak of Lipa to include these nearby suburban and rural towns where the daily life and tourism is essentially connected to the city .
#Text=Lipa city proper
#Text=Balete , to the northwest
#Text=Mataasnakahoy , to the west
#Text=Lipa is a medium-size city , with a population of 332,386 , according to the 2015 Census .

#Text=The city is undergoing fast urbanization , and is the largest city in Batangas , but Batangas City still comes first in terms of economic development , as it has the Philippines 's second most important port and interisland transport hub .
#Text=To Manileño folks , Lipa is associated with the Batangueño favourite , the kapeng barako ( Arabica coffee ) , introduced by the Spaniards .
#Text=Kapeng barako production once served an important source of income to locals , but it died out in favor of other agricultural products and commercial developments .
#Text=The town of Mataasnakahoy is practically a suburb of Lipa , just behind the Fernando Airbase , and is closer to the city in its growth .
#Text=Balete does not have much growth as Mataasnakahoy , but can still be considered a suburb , connected by a national road through the eastern slope of Taal Lake .
#Text=Their local population rely on fishing and agriculture , and usually travel to Lipa to shop , study , and work .
#Text=Lipa is the seat of its namesake Roman Catholic archdiocese , the Archdiocese of Lipa , founded in 1910 .
#Text=Majority of the city 's population are Catholic , and church attendance remains high despite slight drops in numbers .
#Text=History
#Text=The original town center of Lipa lied in what is now Mataasnakahoy , in the slopes of Taal Lake .
#Text=The old town center ( Lumang Lipa ) was destroyed by the 1755 eruption of Taal Volcano , and only a bit of it remains today .
#Text=The current downtown became the new site of the town center after 1755 .
#Text=Under royal decree , the new Lipa was elevated into a city in 1887 .
#Text=Lipa sustained heavy damage during World War II , and was almost destroyed by Japanese dive bombers .
#Text=Lipa also caught international attention in 1948 after the supposed Mary Mediatrix apparition , which has not been been confirmed true by the Vatican .
#Text=Climate
#Text=The climate is tropical , heavily influenced by the monsoon .
#Text=Daily temperatures can be as high as or low as , and there is less variation in temperature .
#Text=Precipitation is influenced by the monsoon , and the wet season is from May to December .
#Text=The city has a very short dry season .
#Text=Average annual rainfall is comparable to Manila .
#Text=Orientation
#Text=Lipa is split into 72 barangays , including the 13 barangays in the Poblacion .
#Text=Some barangays of interest are :
#Text=Dagatan - The Malarayat Golf Course and County Club and Fiesta World Mall lies in this barangay .
#Text=International schools are also concentrated around this area
#Text=Marawoy - Here , you may find the City Hall and SM City Lipa .
#Text=Mataas Na Lupa - This area has a growing nightlife and a gentrifying environment .
#Text=Here you can find Robinsons Place Lipa , the Big Ben shopping center , and the city 's top educational institution , De La Salle Lipa .
#Text=You can also go into classy restaurants and cafés on the rise in the area .
#Text=Local orientation
#Text=divide Lipa City proper into two parts , the Downtown and the Uptown .
#Text=The " Downtown " included the Poblacion area , where Lipa Cathedral and the public market are found .

#Text=The area along Ayala Highway ( Jose P. Laurel Highway , or Route 4 ) is called " Uptown " , a fastly gentrifying section of the city , composed of barangays Mataas na Lupa , Balintawak , and Marawoy .

#Text=With developments of large malls , commercial space , and development of mid-range restaurants , bars and cafés ( e.g. Starbucks , The Coffee Bean and Tea Leaf , Army Navy , Shakey 's ) , the Uptown also houses Lipa 's growing nightlife .
#Text=By bus
#Text=SM City Lipa Grand Terminal ( At SM City Lipa ) .
#Text=Central terminal for buses headed for Lipa .
#Text=Jeepneys and tricycles are available from the terminal .
#Text=Buses come from Manila and Batangas City , mainly via STAR Tollway or the older Jose P. Laurel Highway .
#Text=Jam has services departing from their Buendia ( Pasay ) or Cubao ( Quezon City ) terminals every 30 minutes ; most head to Lemery .
#Text=DLTB has hourly departures from Buendia and Cubao as well .
#Text=Fares are at about ₱160-180 per head .
#Text=ALPS the Bus and ito regional bus line , JAPS , has frequent trips from Batangas City .
#Text=Fare is at about ₱50
#Text=By car
#Text=Lipa is well accessible from the tolled Southern Tagalog Arterial Road ( STAR Tollway ) .
#Text=Those avoiding tolls may take the Jose P. Laurel Highway , but watch out for traffic jams , especially during school days .
#Text=From San Pablo , Laguna , the main route is the Lipa-Alaminos Road , which mostly takes you through coconut plantations , mountains and jungle .
#Text=From Quezon Province , take the Batangas-Quezon Road ( Route 435 ) , then follow Lipa-Padre Garcia Road ( Route 431 ) , which becomes P. Torres Street as it approaches downtown .

#Text=There is a bypass road being constructed from Route 435 in Padre Garcia to Lipa-Alaminos Road in Dagatan , providing a bypass to Route 431 and Lipa 's downtown , but is not expected to open until around 2020 or 2021 .
#Text=By jeepney
#Text=You can take the Batangas – Lipa jeepney route if coming from Batangas City or San Jose , with frequent service from Balagtas or San Jose Poblacion .
#Text=Fares range from ₱12-42 depending on originating point .
#Text=Express service
#Text=Balibago-Lipa City via Tanauan .
#Text=Departs from Target Mall in Santa Rosa , with a stopover at Tanauan , and arrives at Robinsons Place Lipa 's jeepney and van terminal .
#Text=Fare is at around ₱96 .
#Text=Get around
#Text=Lipa 's old downtown , the Poblacion , is characterized by a rough grid of streets , characteristic of Spanish-era town centers .
#Text=Many streets are narrow , more suited for pedestrian traffic than cars .
#Text=With the exception of large shopping malls , the downtown hosts most local businesses and the public market , a staple of Philippine city/town centers .
#Text=Car travel is inadvisable in the Poblacion , as parking is hard to find , and pedestrians practically cross everywhere .
#Text=Most parts of the city can be reached by jeepney and tricycle .
